Text.Value: *There is nothing left to speak of. His friend is gone, his focus now diverted to the nurturing  of Omeluum's legacy - his work.*

EditorData.logicalname: Told Blurg his friend is dead

Text.Value: For example, it is quite bright up here. I had forgotten about the malady known as 'sunburn'.
In the field, seeking further subjects for study. Though it has been gone for longer than I anticipated.
Omeluum is most likely safe and well, and simply absorbed in its work. However, it would put my mind at rest to confirm it, if you happen across its path.

EditorData.NodeContext: Trying to sound calm, but very worried

Text.Value: Of course. I should get back to my research.
Omeluum believed the answer to this riddle lay within the city walls, and held some connection to the cult of the Absolute.
Of course. And for a friend such as yourself, I'm happy to apply our full academic discount.
A field of research I am glad exists - it will be of immense value for those exposed to it on a more regular basis.
I've become quite the expert on my tadpole since we last met.
I am glad to see you well. I see your tadpole remains in its state of suspension.
You again. I hope you left your violent impulses back in the Underdark. They have no place in the Society of Brilliance.
Naturally. The Underdark provided us with some most unusual salvage. Plenty to keep an inquiring mind busy.
Omeluum tells me I have you to thank for its safe return.
Is there something I can do for you?
I thought you were conducting research in the Underdark?
Now is not the time for concern - now is a time for action. Go out and find your friend!
Have you anything to trade?
I'll track Omeluum down. Where was it headed?
We'll depart when this Absolute army is defeated. I understand you are involved in the matter.
Leave.
We are required to attend the Lodge from time to time, in order to present our findings to the Society's members.
Is there anything I can do for you, friend?
I hear there's an unguent that protects against the sun's powers...
Leave.
My gloom-lit friend. I take it you were curious to see the Society of Brilliance for yourself?
My star-crossed friend. I take it you were curious to see the Society of Brilliance for yourself?
My surface-dwelling friend. I take it you were curious to see the Society of Brilliance for yourself?
If there's any conclusion to be drawn from this, I think it's that Omeluum and I are safest back in the Underdark.
To jump to action without evidence is hardly becoming of the Society of Brilliance.
Of course. I always carry samples, in case there are inquiring minds looking to purchase them.
I am doing my best to conduct my own research in its absence.
Our research there must continue. We may not be able to fight on the front lines as you do, but we may yet do some good for those who call it home.
Unfortunately my second-hand knowledge does not compare to the innate understanding Omeluum brings to such study.
It seems your aggression has its uses after all. Omeluum tells me I've you to thank for its safe return.
The lure of knowledge is a hard one to resist. Even where it requires us to endure discomfort.
We will not let you leave empty-handed, though. Make sure you speak to Omeluum before you leave.
I usual tell people to keep to the city - but in your case, perhaps the wilds are safer.
My gloom-lit friend. How long has it been?
My star-crossed friend. How long has it been?
My surface-dwelling friend. How long has it been?
A fair assumption. Omeluum is not given to strong emotion, but I know it regrets the damage caused by others of its kind.
I had the distinct impression it was intentionally keeping its hypothesis from me. As though even the theory would be enough to put me in danger.

EditorData.NodeContext: Trying to sound calm, but very worried

Text.Value: Have you anything to trade?
I may be indulging myself somewhat with its title, but I do believe our research harbours such potential. I only hope the Society's members agree.
Perhaps Omeluum prefers to work alone, given its connection to the subject matter.
Then I wish you a pleasant day. May it bring you a wealth of discoveries.
We know the risks when we go out into the field, but to lose my friend in such a way would have been most disheartening.
After observing the nature of your tadpole's stasis, we felt it wise to report back to the Society.
Your tadpole's stasis is a most curious area of study. I will have much to share with Omeluum upon its return.
I admit, I'm somewhat concerned. We are usually sticklers for updating one another on our progress.
I'm familiar with that particular flavour of discomfort. Why did you leave the Underdark?
Why did you leave the Underdark?
I'll head out now - see if I can pick up Omeluum's trail.
Where is Omeluum?
What's the subject of your treatise?
As for me - I'll remain indoors. The Society's library will keep me quite busy until I return to my research in the Underdark.
We meet again. This time without the need for violence, I hope.

EditorData.NodeContext: Not impressed with the player, but moving on from your conflict

Text.Value: Omeluum went out into the city to seek out further undeveloped infections like yours, but I have heard nothing since.
Nothing for now.
My research partner prefers to avoid crowds, and so has remained in the Underdark to monitor our zurkhwood samples.
I see you have not yet undergone ceremorphosis. I can only assume your tadpole remains in stasis.
Leave.
Have you anything to trade?
Your case has set us on quite the detour from our planned expedition work. We've thought about very little else.
I'll leave you to it.
I am eager to return myself, but I must prepare my treatise before I depart. Sharing knowledge is one of the Society's most important tenets.
I hope our gifts will provide you with some meaningful assistance in fighting the evil Omeluum uncovered. Do let us know how you get on.
You should stick to reading books. It's much safer.
Speaking of which, I should get back to annotating my references. Is there anything else I can do for you?
'The Underused Underdark: Applications for Zurkhwood in Unlocking the Future of Subterranean Civilisations.'
Have you anything to trade?
I know a wizard over in Elturel who'd disagree. Incurable paper cuts are no laughing matter.
You have? I would love to hear your conclusions, but it would not feel right to do so without my research partner.
Poor Omeluum. This is terrible news. Our research is meant for good - it should not get us killed.
Why that would be, I can only theorise myself. It is rather outside my area of expertise.
Bravery is no bad thing. In fact, your research could be invaluable for my cause.
Of course. And given the aid you provided to Omeluum, I'm happy to offer you Society member rates.
I have bad news. Your friend the mind flayer, Omeluum, is dead.
Omeluum would want me to continue its work, and I have a rudimentary understanding of its hypothesis.

Synopsis:
Dialog with Blurg in the Lodge.

Blurg is present there in case the gith massacre hasn't happened and players have met it in UND.
